I applaud Google/YouTube TV and Disney/Hulu + Live TV adding C-SPAN and hope additional streaming services follow their example in the near future.

While these are appropriate roles for Congress, the root issues won’t be solved by Washington. California is going to have to make changes to fix its broken home insurance market. As the incoming Chairman of the Housing and Insurance Subcommittee on the HFSC, there will be a full accounting of California’s broken insurance market as the recovery cost figures begin to emerge.

California has placed political preferences ahead of sound actuarial principles for far too long, harming consumers as costs go up and availability goes down. As Congress assesses the damage, debates the recovery, and supports the people of California, I will strongly advocate for policies that adhere to risk-based pricing principles to support consumers and taxpayers.

In response to this affordability and availability crisis last month, California’s Insurance Commissioner finally allowed for the few remaining insurance firms in state to use catastrophe pricing and price in reinsurance in policy writing. While these reforms are welcome, more action is needed to foster competition, entice carriers to return, and ensure policyholders, and ultimately, taxpayers are not paying for the mistakes of California bureaucrats.

Concerns have grown that the claim costs on these devastating fires will bankrupt the FAIR pool of funds, with private insurers and their policyholders on the hook for covering the excess claims. This comes on top of the already high costs many consumers face due to California’s other poor state regulatory choices.

These misguided decisions have pushed out private insurance firms, forcing more homeowners into California’s FAIR plan, the state’s insolvent fire insurance pool of last resort. FAIR’s exposure has tripled to $458 billion as of last September, with only $700 million cash on hand to pay claims.

Additionally, California’s requirement that carriers have to seek state approval before adjusting pricing, which in many cases takes months if approved at all, has distorted the insurance market and made it very difficult for carriers to offer consumers the products they need to protect their homes.

While our state-based insurance model has long been successful, it is not immune to misguided policy choices, particularly in states with liberals and progressives in positions of power. California has consistently been the prime offender, with the Insurance Commissioner enacting onerous mandates and refusing to allow insurance companies to incorporate the cost of reinsurance or use standard industry practices like catastrophe models to predict future risk.

Politicians have blamed the insurance industry for their troubles. The truth is private carriers were forced out of California due to government mandates that do not allow the industry to appropriately price for risk and costs.
